ABSTRACT
In this paper, we present an intelligent news recommendation system capable of dynamically ranking items by capturing complex semantic features from text and adapting to shifting user preferences. By combining Natural Language Processing (NLP) embeddings, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) for localized feature extraction, and Reinforcement Learning (RL) via contextual bandits, we propose a responsive, content-aware recommender system evaluated on the Microsoft News Dataset (MIND).

INTRODUCTION
Traditional collaborative filtering often struggles with the cold-start problem inherent in the fast-paced news domain. Our project combines deep feature extraction with dynamic policy learning to overcome this. The Minimum Viable Product (MVP) is an offline simulation framework comprising an embedding-based ranker coupled with a contextual bandit agent. System performance is evaluated using simulated cumulative rewards (Click-Through Rate) evaluated via unbiased offline replay techniques.

DATASET AND PREPROCESSING
The project utilizes the MIcrosoft News Dataset (MIND-small). MIND is constructed from the anonymized behavior logs of Microsoft News website users.
During Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA), we identified a massive class imbalance, observing a baseline Click-Through Rate (CTR) of approximately 4.8%. This sparsity confirms that a simple greedy model would fail, justifying our use of Contextual Bandits for active exploration. We finalized an 80/20 chronological split based on impression timestamps to prevent data leakage.

MODELING METHODOLOGY
The system architecture integrates three core artificial intelligence domains:
3.1 NLP & CNN Components
Pre-trained dense language models generate semantic embeddings for candidate news articles. To satisfy the core CNN requirement, a 1D Text-CNN acts as a parallel feature extractor. Operating over word embeddings, the CNN applies varying filter sizes (2, 3, and 4 n-grams) to capture critical local patterns in news titles (e.g., catching specific entity relationships). The outputs are max-pooled and concatenated to form a robust 128-dimensional context vector representing the news item.
3.2 Reinforcement Learning Component
The CNN features define the context passed to a Contextual Bandit agent (LinUCB). The bandit observes the current candidate contexts, calculates the expected reward alongside an uncertainty bound (controlled by alpha), and selects an article to recommend. The environment is managed via a Replay Simulator that issues binary rewards (1 for a click, 0 for a skip).

EXPERIMENTS AND EVALUATION
To validate our system, we conducted two ablations and an error slice analysis.
4.1 Ablation 1: RL Exploration Rate
We evaluated the LinUCB agent using a low exploration rate (alpha=0.1) versus a high exploration rate (alpha=0.5). Our learning curves demonstrated that while a higher alpha explores more aggressively early on, alpha=0.1 achieved a faster convergence and a higher cumulative reward rate over time, as excessive exploration penalizes the CTR in a sparse environment.
4.2 Ablation 2: NLP Embedding Dimensions
We compared the TextCNN feature extractor using an embedding dimension of 32 versus 128. The 128-dimensional embedding yielded a smoother learning curve and higher terminal reward, proving that richer semantic representation significantly aids the bandit in making accurate contextual matches.
4.3 Slice & Error Analysis
A categorical slice analysis revealed disparate performance across news genres. The model achieved high CTRs in niche categories (e.g., 'Finance') where vocabulary is highly specific but struggled with broad categories (e.g., 'Entertainment') due to semantic overlap and user unpredictability.

ETHICS AND POLICY
To mitigate "Filter Bubbles," our LinUCB agent utilizes upper confidence bounds to force the exploration of novel content, preventing ideological echo chambers. Furthermore, strict adherence to the MIND dataset’s anonymization protocols was maintained; all user IDs were securely hashed, and no external data linkage was attempted, ensuring total privacy compliance.

CONCLUSION
We successfully developed and evaluated a hybrid CNN-RL news recommender. The integration of a 1D Text-CNN with a LinUCB agent proved effective in offline simulation, successfully balancing the exploration-exploitation trade-off while capturing rich textual features from news titles.
